---
title: Coley Massaman Curry with Limey Jasmine Rice
description: This recipe mixes sweet, fragrant spices, creamy coconut milk and the salty, savoury taste of peanut butter for the perfect Thai-inspired massaman curry. Our chefs have used coley as its flavour and texture (which is often compared to cod) are great with such intense flavour.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/coley-massaman-curry-3fa8e2a0-bc1cba55.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipecards/card/coley-massaman-curry-5dc40975622f8a38f5146a49-39258edf.pdf
time required: 35 minutes
cuisine: Thai
course: main course
nutrition:
  calories: 680 kcal
  fat: 28 g
  saturated fat: 17 g
  carbohydrates: 75 g
  sugar: 11 g
  protein: 31 g
  sodium: 1 g
  serving size: 476
author: Mimi Morley
source: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipes/coley-massaman-curry-5dc40975622f8a38f5146a49
servings: 2
---

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced). Trim the @carrot{1} then halve lengthways no need to peel. Thinly slice widthways. Trim the @spring onion{1} and thinly slice. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Zest and halve the @lime{1}. Chop the @coley fillet{2} into 2cm chunks and pop into a #bowl{}, add half the lime zest, a squeeze of juice and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{}. Set aside.

Pour the @water for the rice{300%ml} into a #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. When boiling, add a pinch of @salt{pinch}, stir in the @jasmine rice{150%g}, lower the heat to medium and pop a #lid{} on the pan. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #frying pan{} on medium high heat. Once hot, add the onion (not the spring onion) and carrot along with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{}. Fry until the veg is really nice and softened, ~{6-8%minutes}. Stir occasionally. Once soft, add the @massaman curry paste{45%g} and garlic. Stir and cook for ~{1%minute}, then pour in the @coconut milk{200%ml} and @water for the curry{150%ml}. Stir in the @peanut butter{1%tbsp} until combined into the sauce.

Bring the mixture to the boil and add a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{}. Reduce the heat to medium and simmer until the mixture has thickened and the carrots are soft, ~{6-8%minutes}. Stir every couple of minutes.

Once the curry has thickened (if it has thickened too much, add a splash of water to loosen it up), taste and add @salt{} and @pepper{} if you feel it needs it. Add the fish to the sauce and carefully stir it in. Cover with a lid or some #foil{} and simmer until the fish is cooked, ~{4-5%minutes}. IMPORTANT: The fish is cooked when opaque all the way through.

Once the fish is cooked, remove the pan from the heat and squeeze in some lime juice. Taste and add more lime juice, salt and pepper if you feel it needs it.

> TIP: Don't stir the mixture too much or you will break up the fish.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and then stir in the remaining lime zest. Serve in #bowls{} and spoon the curry on top. Sprinkle over the spring onion, serve with any remaining lime chopped into wedges and enjoy!